AN ACT relating to offenders; requiring the Director of the
Department of Corrections to adopt regulations governing
the diet of offenders in the custody of the Department;
and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires the Chief Medical Officer to: (1) examine the nutritional
2 adequacy of the diet of incarcerated offenders; and (2) submit a semiannual report
3 to the Board of State Prison Commissioners concerning the operations of the
4 Department of Corrections related to the dietary needs of incarcerated offenders.
5 (NRS 209.382) Section 1 of this bill requires the Director of the Department of
6 Corrections, with the approval of the Board of State Prison Commissioners, to
7 adopt regulations to be instituted at each institution or facility which govern the
8 food served at institutions or facilities operated by the Department. Under section
9 1, the regulations must: (1) require the Department and each institution or facility
10 operated by the Department to adopt the Good Food Purchasing Program or its
11 successor program; (2) prohibit the Department and any institution or facility
12 operated by the Department from entering into a contract or other agreement with a
13 for-profit food vendor; and (3) require a licensed dietitian or registered dietitian to
14 approve each meal or menu item provided to offenders in accordance with certain
15 dietary guidelines. Section 1 also requires the Director, to the extent money is
16 available, to establish and carry out a prison farm program to be instituted in each
17 institution or facility operated by the Department.
